Part one1:

Here I attempted to create an epoch visualization and symbol chart similar to that which I did for
assignment 2. Sadly, the code was not able to function properly but DOES accurately analyze
the frequency of the data, correctly distinguishing between P300 and N400 signifiers within the
simulated data. The goal of this program is to visualize the brain activity across four channels
(AF7, AF8, TP9, TP10) as well as showcase when the data recorded the correct stimuli
I intend to make this stimulus identify the correct answer to an incorrect statement from a
question from the show ‚ÄúUm, Actually‚Äù where contestants are required to identify the mistake in
statements about pop culture or sci-fi fiction background lore. Not only do they have to weed out
the mistakes but they also have to correct them, based on their knowledge of the television
series or video game. The correct stimulus elicits a response of a positive 300ms value.
Simultaneously, this program also analyzes when contestants initially identify the mistake in the
statement, as not all contestants know enough information to correct the mistake. Identifying the
mistake requires identifying the error eliciting a response of a negative 400ms value. Thus, this
program showcases when a contestant would a) identify the mistake in the statement and b)
correctly identify the correction associated with that statement.

Part two2:

that, if it shows a blue circle stays on the screen as a ‚Äúcorrect response‚Äù versus if it shows a red
circle, its overlapped by a hazard sign (orange triangle overlayed by a white triangle). This,
instead, showcases three different symbols. This is because:
This was an older concept graphic than part one; here I intended to pair the graphic as a
representation of an educational video series that would use preface examples with the
adjective ‚Äúblue‚Äù (i.e., blue dog, blue oil, blue policy) and this would distinguish functional and
correct examples from bad or incorrect comparisons.
Through both of these parts I‚Äôve learned that this is so incredibly difficult and even with the
assistance of information, to undergo these kinds of projects more time and utlization of the

respond to overdoses on the street?
